node.text:
From Miami to Maine … that’s a wrap on our epic ‘Mother Nature, Let’s Do This!’ road trip! Dogfish Head founders Sam & Mariah Calagione ventured along the eastern seaboard to learn more about the amazing work being done by our partners @nature_org! A big thanks to each and every TNC chapter that took the time to share their incredible efforts and the broader TNC team for all their work along the way! To learn more about the environmental issues facing us on a global and local level, as well as our work with TNC, be sure to hop on over to dogfish.com/mothernature (link in bio)! 🌱 #MotherNatureLetsDoThis

*Dogfish Head is a proud supporter of The Nature Conservancy (TNC) and its mission to conserve the lands & waters on which all life depends’ (www.nature.org). TNC does not endorse any specific product, including all those visible in the road trip docuseries. Purchase of Dogfish Head products will not result in a contribution to TNC. Learn more at www.dogfish.com/TNC.

node.title: Mother Nature, Let’s Do This! Road Trip - We Did It!

node.text: Have you tried our Blue Hen Pilsner yet? This first-state-focused brew started as a brewpub exclusive at our Rehoboth brewpub, and it’s all about celebrating our roots in our home state of Delaware … and lovingly named after our state bird! Check out the video below to learn more from Sam and Brewing Ambassador Bryan about this crisp and refreshing pilsner that we brew with Delmarva grown and malted barley from our friends at @proximity.malt! Blue Hen Pilsner is hitting store shelves now in our Hoppy Variety Pack – try it out and let us know what you think! 🍺🐓💙 #offcentered #craftbeer

node.title: Learn more about Blue Hen Pilsner with Sam & Bryan!

It’s the final episode of our ‘Mother Nature, Let’s Do This!’ journey. After weeks of outdoor site visits along the eastern seaboard, Sam & Mariah venture to four remaining spots to see how collective action can have a lasting impact. node.text:
It’s been months in the making … an epic road trip from Florida to Maine with one very clear mission: learn more about the environmental issues facing us globally and on a localized level. And who better to help us along our ‘Mother Nature, Let’s Do This!’ journey than our longtime partners @nature_org (TNC). In a four-part docuseries, watch as Dogfish Head founders Sam & Mariah stop at 13 distinct sites to tackle issues like oyster aquaculture and restoration, land and water conservation, and so much more. In this episode, Sam & Mariah get their feet wet (literally!) with visits to Blowing Rocks Preserve @natureflorida, Goldbug Island Living Shoreline in South Carolina and the Black River Preserve @tnc_nc. To learn more about ‘Mother Nature, Let’s Do This!’ and our work with TNC, head to dogfish.com/mothernature! 🌱 #MotherNatureLetsDoThis

*Dogfish Head is a proud supporter of The Nature Conservancy (TNC) and its mission to conserve the lands & waters on which all life depends’ (www.nature.org). TNC does not endorse any specific product, including all those visible in the road trip docuseries. Purchase of Dogfish Head products will not result in a contribution to TNC. Learn more at www.dogfish.com/TNC.

node.text: At Dogfish Head, we rely on the goodness of Mother Nature to provide us with the beautiful and bountiful culinary ingredients used in our off-centered beverages and dishes. And with a restless desire to explore at the heart of everything we do, Dogfish Head founders Sam & Mariah Calagione were eager to learn more about the environmental issues facing us globally and on a localized level. So, they packed up and hit the road for a month-long journey in our backyard that is the eastern seaboard. From oyster reefs to the very first @nature_org preserve, we’ve captured it all. Follow along over the coming weeks as we unpack and reflect on an incredible journey. 🌱 #MotherNatureLetsDoThis #conserveandprotect

node.text: Taking a moment to say thank you to those of you who have shared your concerns in the comments below. We hear you, we see you, and we’re with you. The spirit of this post was to celebrate you, the craft beer drinker, and the amazing community that often gathers to enjoy the art that is craft beer. But we see now, we missed the mark and for that we’re sincerely sorry. Unfortunately, as our community has grown, there has no doubt been inexcusable behaviors that have come to light. We’re hopeful that the dialogue and work that has been started continues and we all push to keep our collective community asshole-free. Internally, our co-workers have been having important conversations to ensure that we create an environment that is free of discrimination and intimidation, and where everyone is treated with respect and dignity.

node.text: Want to SEA a little bit of the magic behind SeaQuench Ale's label artwork in action?
